{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:28:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:28:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"805"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/805"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.06,0.51,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102408"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/805"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84879"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44863"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102408"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department of a rural hospital after falling three metres head-first onto concrete at a building site. He was not wearing a helmet. Initially he was able to walk, but became confused 30 minutes after the fall, prompting his colleagues to drive him to hospital. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn A to E assessment has been carried out and he has been successfully intubated by a colleague. On further examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 40/min, blood pressure 160/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 100% (intubated), and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He responds to pain with withdrawal, eye opening and incoherent sounds. There is a haematoma over the right temple. His right pupil is dilated with absent light reflexes, while the left pupil is normal size with normal light reflexes. The nearest neurosurgical centre is 60 minutes away by road.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right-sided burr hole","Left-sided burr hole","Intravenous mannitol","Intravenous dexamethasone","Cranial X-ray"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of extradural haemorrhage: a lucid interval following head trauma to the temple region (where the middle meningeal artery is vulnerable to injury), followed by rapid neurological deterioration. The Cushing\u0027s reflex (bradycardia and hypertension) and unilateral dilated pupil indicate critical intracranial hypertension with impending uncal herniation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous mannitol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate intervention. This hyperosmolar agent reduces intracranial pressure while arrangements are made for urgent neurosurgical transfer. The dose is typically 1g/kg. Hypertonic saline is an acceptable alternative if mannitol is unavailable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eright-sided burr hole\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft-sided burr hole\u003C/strong\u003E should not be attempted in a non-neurosurgical centre. While historically performed in rural settings, emergency burr holes should only be considered after discussion with the receiving neurosurgeon, and not before medical management has been optimised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous dexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for traumatic brain injury. While steroids have a role in reducing oedema around brain tumours, they have not been shown to improve outcomes in trauma and may be harmful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECranial X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would delay definitive management and add little value. CT imaging would be ideal but should not delay transfer if unavailable. The clinical features alone are sufficient to justify urgent neurosurgical referral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe priorities in this scenario are: protecting the airway (already achieved through intubation), initiating hyperosmolar therapy, arranging urgent transfer, and maintaining adequate cerebral perfusion pressure through careful blood pressure management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Extradural haemorrhage classically presents with a lucid interval followed by rapid deterioration within hours of head injury","Cushing\u0027s reflex (bradycardia and hypertension) indicates critically raised intracranial pressure","Hyperosmolar therapy and early intubation are priorities in severe head injury when neurosurgical care is not immediately available"],"references":["Reed D.\u00a0Initial Management of Closed Head Injury in Adults. In: Adult trauma clinical practice guidelines, NSW Health [online]. 2nd\u00a0Edition. 2011.\u00a0Available at: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/195150/NSW-Health-Initial-management-closed-head-injuries-full.pdf","Wakai A, McCabe A, Roberts I, Schierhout G. Mannitol for acute traumatic brain injury. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2013 Aug 5;2013(8):CD001049. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7050611/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84879"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"805"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84879"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T10:52:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T10:52:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"805"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102408"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description